{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"de4878619605b034b6dffdf6e81c4a8afb3e95f2e57d7758444c12cc4a980299","slug":"pages.m11-binomial-random-variables-2-of-4","location":"/pages/145-m11-binomial-random-variables-2-of-4.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Binomial Random Variables (2 of 4)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"thumbnail":"/build/image080-a368cab5aec22d9b6e816fee8faf24f5.gif","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"145-m11-binomial-random-variables-2-of-4.md","url":"/build/145-m11-binomial-ran-83effa02951503db08ae7b04e32d669a.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"CmcpfjcPbN"}],"key":"nXScfNWK5Y"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Fit the binomial model when appropriate, and use it to perform simple calculations.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"XmVizZjt4x"}],"key":"owPe6RbxoD"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now that we understand what a binomial random variable is, and when it arises, it’s time to discuss its probability distribution. We’ll start with a simple example and then generalize to a formula.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"v4P90Asymn"}],"key":"gL9rUTBrGN"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example: Deck of Cards","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"Q1zTrdWu2o"}],"key":"buVQABlSzU"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"Consider a regular deck of 52 cards, in which there are 13 cards of each suit: hearts, diamonds, clubs and spades. We select 3 cards at random *with replacement*. Let X be the number of diamond cards we got (out of the 3).\n\nWe have 3 trials here, and they are independent (since the selection is with replacement). The outcome of each trial can be either success (diamond) or failure (not diamond), and the probability of success is 1/4 in each of the trials.\n\nX, then, is binomial with n = 3 and p = 1/4.\n\nLet's build the probability distribution of X as we did in the chapter on probability distributions. Recall that we begin with a table in which we:\n\n- record all possible outcomes in 3 selections, where each selection may result in success (a diamond, D) or failure (a non-diamond, N).\n- find the value of X that corresponds to each outcome.\n- use simple probability principles to find the probability of each outcome.\n\n```{figure} images/image078.gif\n:alt: A table of all of the outcomes. Here is the data in the table, given in &quot;Outcome: Value of X, Probability&quot; format: NNN: 0, 3/4 × 3/4 × 3/4; NND: 1, 3/4 × 3/4 × 1/4; NDN: 1, 3/4 × 1/4 × 3/4; DNN: 1, 1/4 × 3/4 × 3/4; NDD: 2, 3/4 × 1/4 × 1/4; DND: 2, 1/4 × 3/4 × 1/4; DDN: 2, 1/4 × 1/4 × 1/4; DDD: 3, 1/4 × 1/4 × 1/4;\n\nA table of all of the outcomes. Here is the data in the table, given in &quot;Outcome: Value of X, Probability&quot; format: NNN: 0, 3/4 × 3/4 × 3/4; NND: 1, 3/4 × 3/4 × 1/4; NDN: 1, 3/4 × 1/4 × 3/4; DNN: 1, 1/4 × 3/4 × 3/4; NDD: 2, 3/4 × 1/4 × 1/4; DND: 2, 1/4 × 3/4 × 1/4; DDN: 2, 1/4 × 1/4 × 1/4; DDD: 3, 1/4 × 1/4 × 1/4;\n```\n\nWith the help of the addition principle, we condense the information in this table to construct the actual probability distribution table:\n\n```{figure} images/image079.gif\n:alt: The probability distribution table has two rows, labeled &quot;X&quot; and &quot;P(X=x).&quot; Here is the data in the table, organized by column. The format is &quot;(X, P(X=x))&quot; 0: 1(3/4)³ 1: 3(1/4)¹(3/4)² 2: 3(1/4)²(3/4)¹ 3: 1(1/4)³\n\nThe probability distribution table has two rows, labeled &quot;X&quot; and &quot;P(X=x).&quot; Here is the data in the table, organized by column. The format is &quot;(X, P(X=x))&quot; 0: 1(3/4)³ 1: 3(1/4)¹(3/4)² 2: 3(1/4)²(3/4)¹ 3: 1(1/4)³\n```","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":34,"column":1}},"key":"K30R4Uulqe"}],"key":"kD8vuHMBFN"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In order to establish a general formula for the probability that a binomial random variable X takes any given value x, we will look for patterns in the above distribution. From the way we constructed this probability distribution, we know that, in general:","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"JocaAvLEpI"}],"key":"tNAJLTJnMf"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image080-a368cab5aec22d9b6e816fee8faf24f5.gif","alt":"P(X=x) = [ Number of possible outcomes with x successes out of 3 ] × [ Probability that each of the outcomes that has x successes out of 3 ]","key":"wWyHTXzGFp","urlSource":"images/image080.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"P(X=x) = [ Number of possible outcomes with x successes out of 3 ] × [ Probability that each of the outcomes that has x successes out of 3 ]","position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"key":"rTuOo5CvHI"}],"key":"s7EqAxK91u"}],"key":"rDdkk8K7j0"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"QpTUCr3I6Y"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s start with the second part, the probability that there will be x successes out of 3, where the probability of success is 1/4. Notice that the fractions multiplied in each case are for the probability of x successes (where each success has a probability of p = 1/4) and the remaining (3 - x) failures (where each failure has probability of 1 - p = 3/4).","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"TESGreCiqU"}],"key":"X7NfzM28yK"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image081-b6f5fd71e847744961e282fe98490a32.gif","alt":"This probability distribution table is nearly the same as the previous one, but presents the calculations in a different way. The table has two rows, labeled &quot;X&quot; and &quot;P(X=x).&quot; Here is the data in the table, organized by column. The format is &quot;(X, P(X=x))&quot; 0: 1 × (1/4)^0 × (3/4)^(3-0); 1: 3 × (1/4)^1 × (3/4)^(3-1); 2: 3 × (1/4)^2 × (3/4)^(3-2); 3: 1 × (1/4)^3 × (3/4)^(3-3);","key":"L61QhMpynx","urlSource":"images/image081.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This probability distribution table is nearly the same as the previous one, but presents the calculations in a different way. The table has two rows, labeled \"X\" and \"P(X=x).\" Here is the data in the table, organized by column. The format is \"(X, P(X=x))\" 0: 1 × (1/4)^0 × (3/4)^(3-0); 1: 3 × (1/4)^1 × (3/4)^(3-1); 2: 3 × (1/4)^2 × (3/4)^(3-2); 3: 1 × (1/4)^3 × (3/4)^(3-3);","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"i6PZ4rZGnt"}],"key":"L3v2EGdZqW"}],"key":"pj1j8ypXxk"}],"enumerator":"2","key":"TBLi81INoL"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So in general:","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"MaEoApq6PT"}],"key":"GwKh3ikQl3"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image082-f92e8766723ca595356f6c2e2be25a94.gif","alt":"[ Probability of each of the outcomes that has x successes out of 3 ] = (1/4)^x × (3/4)^(3-x)","key":"lNVbBR4u17","urlSource":"images/image082.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"[ Probability of each of the outcomes that has x successes out of 3 ] = (1/4)^x × (3/4)^(3-x)","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"R9YybPGPst"}],"key":"Qy4Oqo4AON"}],"key":"tnsu6E1sSa"}],"enumerator":"3","key":"H8mXqFhj3D"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s move on to talk about the number of possible outcomes with x successes out of three. Here it is harder to see the pattern, so we’ll give the following mathematical result.","position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"key":"LPCU7lHHfy"}],"key":"eF6PL09Emq"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Result","position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"key":"exj57NucGx"}],"identifier":"result","label":"Result","html_id":"result","implicit":true,"key":"iNG3HNLUOo"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Consider a random experiment that consists of n trials, each one ending up in either success or failure. The number of possible outcomes in the sample space that have exactly k successes out of n is:","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"aW9zIiCYn7"}],"key":"fPRZQ86Wks"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.4001em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8801em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">!</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)!</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">!</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"Zr9djHirrJ"}],"key":"MjPHfWT8q6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note that n! is read “n factorial” and is defined to be the product 1 * 2 * 3 * ... * n. 0! is defined to be 1.","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"key":"q4Jb1vrY3q"}],"key":"q3RMzDBJXr"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example: Ear Piercings","position":{"start":{"line":71,"column":1},"end":{"line":71,"column":1}},"key":"pZFXJpDFzJ"}],"key":"EjJGq4IVlJ"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"You choose 12 male college students at random and record whether they have any ear piercings (success) or not. There are many possible outcomes to this experiment (actually, 4,096 of them!).\n\nIn how many of the possible outcomes of this experiment are there exactly 8 successes (students who have at least one ear pierced)?\n\nThere is no way that we would start listing all these possible outcomes. The result above comes to our rescue.\n\nThe result says that in an experiment like this, where you repeat a trial n times (in our case, we repeat it n = 12 times, once for each student we choose), the number of possible outcomes with exactly 8 successes (out of 12) is:\n\n$\\frac{12!}{8!(12-8)!}=\\frac{1*2*3*...*12}{(1*2*3*...*8)(1*2*3*4)}=495$","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":80,"column":1}},"key":"Xdl1rbWx6R"}],"key":"WadMS7gkeS"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"aL3Z4leYmH"}],"key":"AmmTNmBt8a"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"fPwO9a4Uz7"}],"key":"gBZpG3PYsN"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example: Cards Revisited","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"c7F73UwIHY"}],"key":"oOXNgch9k8"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"Let's go back to our example, in which we have n = 3 trials (selecting 3 cards). We saw that there were 3 possible outcomes with exactly 2 successes out of 3. The result confirms this since:\n\n$\\frac{3!}{2!(3-2)!}=\\frac{1*2*3}{(1*2)(1)}=\\frac{6}{2}=3$","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"LD01WNXPbc"}],"key":"tcdYcXa2v0"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In general, then","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"key":"pMgEJ4JNgV"}],"key":"srt6B3zUQ8"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image086-fa73dd60f7ed88602220d3e309b862e2.gif","alt":"[ Number of possible outcomes with x successes out of 3 ] = ( 3! ) / [ x! × (3-x)! ]","key":"UrcjFycLUy","urlSource":"images/image086.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"[ Number of possible outcomes with x successes out of 3 ] = ( 3! ) / [ x! × (3-x)! ]","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"key":"VlAUMcSMLt"}],"key":"VQoKAWRLdE"}],"key":"wWlfyqiKD2"}],"enumerator":"4","key":"dC5HpNmzeJ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":103,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Putting it all together, we get that the probability distribution of X, which is binomial with n = 3 and p = 1/4 is:","position":{"start":{"line":103,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"key":"FJJuClnyrd"}],"key":"CpS0mYhZvq"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"inlineMath","value":"P(X=x)=\\frac{3!}{x!(3-x)!}(\\frac{1}{4})^{x}(\\frac{3}{4})^{3-x}forx=0,1,2,3","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi>x</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(X=x)=\\frac{3!}{x!(3-x)!}(\\frac{1}{4})^{x}(\\frac{3}{4})^{3-x}forx=0,1,2,3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"m